Trial # 1
Original Symptoms:
	 Raynaud's Syndrome
	 Edema
	 Weight Loss
	 Periungal Erythema
	 Fatigue
	 Falling Episodes
	 Gottron Papule
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Lymphadenopathy
	 Dysphagia
	 Dyspnea on Exertion
Translated Symptoms:
	 Finger turning blue
	 Leg swelling
	 Weight Loss
	 Red Cuticles
	 Fatigue
	 Loss of Coordination
	 Rash on hands
	 Rash on eyelids
	 Cannot wash hair
	 Bumps on neck
	 Trouble swallowing solids
	 Trouble breathing with activity
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 60,  The patient presents with a combination of skin rash, fatigue, muscle weakness (loss of coordination), weight loss, trouble washing hair, and difficulty swallowing solids which are all consistent with Juvenile Dermatomyositis. The blue fingers, leg swelling, and rash on hands and eyelids can also be seen in this condition.
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 20,  The patient's symptoms of rash on hands, rash on eyelids, fatigue, weight loss, and joint involvement (loss of coordination) are commonly seen in Systemic Lupus Erythematosus. The blue fingers, leg swelling, and trouble breathing with activity can also be associated with SLE.
	 3, Systemic Sclerosis, 10,  The patient's symptoms of blue fingers, leg swelling, red cuticles, trouble swallowing solids, and trouble breathing with activity are suggestive of systemic sclerosis. The rash on hands and eyelids and bumps on the neck can also be seen in this condition.
	 4, Kawasaki Disease, 5,  The patient's symptoms of rash on hands, rash on eyelids, bumps on the neck, trouble swallowing solids, and trouble breathing with activity can be seen in Kawasaki Disease. The blue fingers and leg swelling may also be present in this condition.
	 5, Toxic Shock Syndrome, 5,  The patient's symptoms of rash on hands, rash on eyelids, and fever along with other systemic symptoms such as fatigue, weight loss, and trouble breathing with activity raise suspicion for Toxic Shock Syndrome. The blue fingers and leg swelling can also be seen in this condition.
Trial # 2
Original Symptoms:
	 Fatigue
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Dyspnea on Exertion
	 Dysphagia
	 Weight Loss
	 Gottron Papule
	 Photosensitive Rashes
	 Periungal Erythema
	 Cutaneous Ulceration
Translated Symptoms:
	 Fatigue
	 Exercise intolerance
	 Rash on eyelids
	 Trouble breathing
	 Pills get stuck in throat
	 Weight Loss
	 Hand rash
	 Can't tolerate sunlight exposure
	 Red Cuticles
	 Sores on hands
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 60,  The patient presents with a combination of fatigue, exercise intolerance, rash on eyelids, hand rash, trouble breathing, weight loss, and intolerance to sunlight exposure, which are all consistent with the clinical presentation of Juvenile Dermatomyositis.
	 2, Eosinophilic esophagitis, 20,  The symptoms of pills getting stuck in the throat, trouble breathing, and weight loss can be indicative of eosinophilic esophagitis, which is a chronic allergic inflammatory condition of the esophagus.
	 3, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 10,  The presence of rash on eyelids, hand rash, red cuticles, and sores on hands may suggest a possible autoimmune condition like Systemic Lupus Erythematosus, which can also present with fatigue, exercise intolerance, and weight loss.
	 4, Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD), 5,  The symptoms of pills getting stuck in the throat, trouble breathing, and weight loss can also be seen in GERD, a condition where stomach acid frequently flows back into the esophagus.
	 5, Celiac Disease, 5,  The combination of weight loss, fatigue, rash on eyelids, and trouble breathing could be seen in Celiac Disease, an autoimmune disorder triggered by gluten consumption leading to malabsorption and various symptoms.
Trial # 3
Original Symptoms:
	 Shawl Sign
	 Fatigue
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Gingivitis
	 Weight Loss
	 Gottron Papule
	 Fever
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Muscle Pain and Tenderness
	 Lymphadenopathy
	 Joint Contracture
	 Arthritis
Translated Symptoms:
	 Rash on Chest and Back
	 Tiredness
	 Activity intolerance
	 Red gums
	 Weight Loss
	 Rash on knuckles
	 Elevated Body Temperature
	 Dark eyelids
	 Flu like ache
	 Bumps under arms
	 Stuck joint
	 Joint pain
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 40,  The patient presents with joint pain, rash on knuckles, activity intolerance, and stuck joint, which are all consistent with Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis.
	 2, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 25,  The patient's symptoms of rash on chest and back, tiredness, activity intolerance, and muscle weakness (evidenced by stuck joint) are suggestive of Juvenile Dermatomyositis.
	 3, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 15,  The combination of rash on chest and back, joint pain, fatigue, and photosensitivity could indicate Systemic Lupus Erythematosus, especially in a young female.
	 4, Kawasaki Disease, 10,  The patient's symptoms of rash, elevated body temperature, red gums, and flu-like aches are consistent with Kawasaki Disease, which commonly affects children.
	 5, Malnutrition, 5,  Weight loss, dark eyelids, bumps under arms, and fatigue may suggest malnutrition as a possible underlying condition in this patient.

Trial # 5
Original Symptoms:
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Falling Episodes
	 Interstitial Lung Disease
	 Gottron Papule
	 Photosensitive Rashes
	 Muscle Pain and Tenderness
	 Raynaud's Syndrome
	 Fatigue
	 Gingivitis
Translated Symptoms:
	 Cannot stand up
	 Loss of Coordination
	 Shorness of breath
	 Hand rash
	 Can't tolerate sunlight exposure
	 Leg pain
	 Cold hands
	 Tiredness
	 Tender gums
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 60,  The patient presents with muscle weakness (cannot stand up), loss of coordination, hand rash, intolerance to sunlight exposure, and tiredness which are consistent with Juvenile Dermatomyositis.
	 2, Vitamin D Deficiency, 20,  The patient's symptoms of leg pain, fatigue, and muscle weakness can be indicative of Vitamin D deficiency, especially in a young child who may not be getting enough sunlight exposure.
	 3, Juvenile Rheumatoid Arthritis, 10,  The symptoms of leg pain, joint tenderness (tender gums), hand rash, and cold hands could be suggestive of Juvenile Rheumatoid Arthritis.
	 4, Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia, 5,  The patient's symptoms of tiredness, shortness of breath, and leg pain could be indicative of a hematologic disorder like Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia.
	 5, Lupus, 5,  The combination of symptoms like fatigue, joint pain (leg pain), rash (hand rash), intolerance to sunlight, and tender gums could be consistent with Lupus.
Trial # 6
Original Symptoms:
	 Malar Rash
	 Joint Contracture
	 Dyspnea on Exertion
	 Photosensitive Rashes
	 Gottron Papule
	 Lymphadenopathy
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Fatigue
Translated Symptoms:
	 Rash on cheeks
	 Contracture
	 Shortness of breath
	 Rash that comes on in sun
	 Rash on knuckles
	 Bumps on neck
	 Cannot wash hair
	 Fatigue
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 70,  The patient presents with a rash on the cheeks, contractures, shortness of breath, rash that worsens in the sun, rash on knuckles, bumps on neck, and difficulty washing hair, which are all consistent with the symptoms of Juvenile Dermatomyositis. Fatigue is also commonly seen in this condition. 
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 20,  SLE can present with a rash on the cheeks (malar rash), rash on knuckles (Gottron's papules), photosensitivity (rash that worsens in the sun), and fatigue. 
	 3, Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma), 5,  The presence of contractures, rash on knuckles, bumps on the neck, and difficulty washing hair are suggestive of systemic sclerosis. Shortness of breath and fatigue can also be seen in this condition. 
	 4, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 3,  Joint contractures, rash on knuckles, and fatigue are common in Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis. 
	 5, Systemic Mastocytosis, 2,  Bumps on the neck could be indicative of mast cell involvement. Rash and shortness of breath can also be seen in systemic mastocytosis.
Trial # 7
Original Symptoms:
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Muscle Pain and Tenderness
	 Fatigue
	 Fever
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Malar Rash

	 Gottron Papule
Translated Symptoms:
	 Cannot raise arms
	 Sore muscles
	 Tiredness
	 Elevated Body Temperature
	 Dark eyelids
	 Rosy cheeks
	 Red Cuticles
	 Rash on knuckles
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 50,  The patient presents with classic symptoms of muscle weakness (cannot raise arms), sore muscles, tiredness, and skin manifestations such as rash on knuckles and dark eyelids.
	 2, Rheumatic Fever, 20,  The combination of elevated body temperature, rosy cheeks, red cuticles, and rash on knuckles may suggest a possible diagnosis of rheumatic fever, especially in a pediatric patient.
	 3, Kawasaki Disease, 15,  The presence of elevated body temperature, red cuticles, and rash on knuckles could be indicative of Kawasaki disease, a condition commonly seen in children.
	 4, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 10,  The symptoms of tiredness, dark eyelids, rosy cheeks, and rash on knuckles could be consistent with a diagnosis of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) in a young patient.
	 5, Viral Infection, 5,  Considering the combination of symptoms such as tiredness, rosy cheeks, red cuticles, and rash on knuckles, a viral infection could also be a possibility in this patient.

Trial # 9
Original Symptoms:
	 Fatigue
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Weight Loss
	 Gottron Papule
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Arthritis
Translated Symptoms:
	 Tiredness
	 Dark eyelids
	 Weight Loss
	 Hand rash
	 Cannot wash hair
	 Hard to move joints
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 60,  The patient's symptoms of tiredness, weight loss, hand rash, and difficulty moving joints are consistent with Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, which is a common cause of joint pain and stiffness in children.
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 20,  SLE can present with tiredness, weight loss, skin rash (including dark eyelids), and joint pain. The combination of these symptoms raises suspicion for SLE in this patient.
	 3, Hypothyroidism, 10,  Hypothyroidism can cause tiredness, weight loss, and darkening of the skin. It can also lead to difficulty moving joints. 
	 4, Dermatomyositis, 5,  Dermatomyositis is a rare inflammatory disease that can cause tiredness, weight loss, skin rash (including dark eyelids), and muscle weakness making it difficult to wash hair or move joints.
	 5, Coeliac Disease, 5,  Coeliac disease can present with tiredness, weight loss, and skin rash. It can also lead to difficulty moving joints due to inflammation in the body.
Trial # 10
Original Symptoms:
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Fever
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Interstitial Lung Disease
	 Arthritis
	 Fatigue
Translated Symptoms:
	 Cannot walk up stairs
	 Elevated Body Temperature
	 Rash on eyelids
	 Shorness of breath
	 Joint pain
	 Fatigue
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 40,  Joint pain, rash on eyelids, fatigue, and difficulty walking up stairs are consistent with Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, which can also present with shortness of breath due to inflammation affecting the lungs.
	 2, Rheumatic Fever, 20,  Elevated body temperature, joint pain, rash on eyelids, and shortness of breath are all symptoms of Rheumatic Fever, which can also cause fatigue and difficulty walking up stairs due to heart involvement.
	 3, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 15,  Rash on eyelids, joint pain, fatigue, and shortness of breath can be seen in SLE, which can also present with elevated body temperature and difficulty walking up stairs due to muscle and joint involvement.
	 4, Kawasaki Disease, 15,  Rash on eyelids, elevated body temperature, joint pain, and fatigue are all symptoms of Kawasaki Disease, which can also lead to shortness of breath and difficulty walking up stairs due to cardiac involvement.
	 5, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 10,  Rash on eyelids, muscle weakness leading to difficulty walking up stairs, joint pain, and fatigue are characteristic features of Juvenile Dermatomyositis, which can also present with elevated body temperature.

Trial # 12
Original Symptoms:
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Gottron Papule
	 Malar Rash
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Cutaneous Ulceration
	 Joint Contracture
	 Fatigue
Translated Symptoms:
	 Cannot raise arms
	 Rash on knuckles
	 Butterfly rash
	 Dark eyelids
	 Sores on hands
	 Joint stuck
	 Tiredness
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 70,  The patient presents with inability to raise arms, rash on knuckles, butterfly rash, dark eyelids, sores on hands, joint stiffness, and tiredness which are all consistent with the symptoms of Juvenile Dermatomyositis, an autoimmune disorder affecting the skin and muscles.
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 15,  The presence of butterfly rash, dark eyelids, joint stiffness, and tiredness could indicate Systemic Lupus Erythematosus, an autoimmune disease that can affect various parts of the body including the skin and joints.
	 3, Rheumatoid Arthritis, 10,  The combination of joint stiffness, tiredness, and the presence of rash on knuckles may suggest Rheumatoid Arthritis, an autoimmune condition that primarily affects the joints.
	 4, Lyme Disease, 3,  Lyme disease can present with joint stiffness, tiredness, and rash-like symptoms on the hands. It is important to consider this especially if the patient has been exposed to areas where ticks are prevalent.
	 5, Hypothyroidism, 2,  Tiredness, joint stiffness, and dark eyelids could be indicative of hypothyroidism, a condition where the thyroid gland does not produce enough hormones. It is important to consider this as a potential cause of the symptoms presented by the patient.

Responses:

	 4, Juvenile Scleroderma, 5,  The presence of hard to move joints, red cuticles, muscle weakness, and shortness of breath could be consistent with Juvenile Scleroderma, a rare autoimmune disease that affects the skin, blood vessels, and internal organs.
	 5, Juvenile Myasthenia Gravis, 5,  Frequent falls, muscle weakness, and shortness of breath are symptoms that may point towards Juvenile Myasthenia Gravis, a neuromuscular disorder causing muscle weakness and fatigue.

	 Sore muscles
	 Rash on hands
	 Fever
	 Fingers turning white
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 40,  The patient presents with symptoms such as painful gums, fatigue, sore muscles, rash on hands, and fingers turning white, which are consistent with Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis. This autoimmune condition can lead to joint pain, fatigue, and a rash on the skin.
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus, 25,  Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE) can present with symptoms such as painful gums, rash on face, fatigue, fever, and fingers turning white. The purple eyelids could also be a manifestation of SLE. This autoimmune disease can affect multiple organs and tissues in the body.
	 3, Kawasaki Disease, 15,  Kawasaki Disease is a possibility given the symptoms of fever, rash on face, and purple eyelids. This condition primarily affects children and can lead to inflammation in blood vessels throughout the body, resulting in symptoms such as fatigue and rash.
	 4, Dermatomyositis, 10,  Dermatomyositis is a rare inflammatory condition that can cause muscle weakness (leading to difficulty walking up stairs), rash on the face and hands, and fatigue. The patient's sore muscles could also be attributed to this condition.
	 5, Raynaud's Phenomenon, 5,  The symptoms of fingers turning white and painful gums could be indicative of Raynaud's Phenomenon, a condition characterized by vasospasm of the blood vessels in response to cold or stress. This could explain the discoloration of the fingers and potentially the gum pain.

	 3, Polymyositis, 15,  Polymyositis is a condition that causes muscle weakness and fatigue, which could explain the inability to raise arms. It can also present with a rash on the knuckles and purple eyelids.
	 4, Scleroderma, 10,  Scleroderma is a connective tissue disorder that can cause skin changes like red cuticles and contractures. It can also lead to difficulty swallowing liquids and fatigue.
	 5, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis (JIA), 5,  JIA can present with joint symptoms like contractures, rash on knuckles, and fatigue. It may also cause difficulty raising arms.

	 2, Scarlet Fever, 20,  The patient's symptoms of fever, rash on cheeks, and red cuticles are suggestive of Scarlet Fever, which is a bacterial infection caused by Group A Streptococcus bacteria.
	 3, Kawasaki Disease, 15,  The patient's symptoms of fever, rash on hands, and joint stiffness can be seen in Kawasaki Disease, a rare childhood illness that causes inflammation in blood vessels.
	 4, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 15,  The patient's symptoms of rash on cheeks, joint stiffness, and muscle weakness could be indicative of Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), an autoimmune disease that can affect multiple organ systems.

	 Joint Contracture
	 Raynaud's Syndrome
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Muscle Pain and Tenderness
	 Weight Loss
	 Gottron Papule
Translated Symptoms:
	 Exercise intolerance
	 Contracture
	 Fingers turning white
	 Dark eyelids
	 Muscle Tenderness
	 Loss of Weight
	 Rash on hands
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 50,  Exercise intolerance, muscle tenderness, weight loss, rash on hands, and dark eyelids are all consistent with Juvenile Dermatomyositis, an autoimmune disease that causes muscle weakness and skin rash.
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 20,  Muscle tenderness, rash on hands, and weight loss can be seen in SLE, which is an autoimmune disease that can affect multiple organs including the skin and muscles.
	 3, Raynaud's disease, 15,  Fingers turning white, exercise intolerance, and rash on hands are suggestive of Raynaud's disease, a condition where there is poor blood circulation to the fingers and toes in response to cold or stress.
	 4, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 10,  Contracture, exercise intolerance, and muscle tenderness can be seen in Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, which is a chronic autoimmune joint condition in children.
	 5, Hypothyroidism, 5,  Weight loss, exercise intolerance, and dark eyelids can be associated with hypothyroidism, a condition where the thyroid gland does not produce enough hormones.

	 4, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 5,  The combination of hand rash, tiredness, red cuticles, rosy cheeks, and bumps under arms could be indicative of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), an autoimmune disease that can affect multiple organ systems. The weight loss and elevated body temperature may also be seen in some patients with SLE.
	 5, Erythromelalgia, 5,  The symptoms of red cuticles, rosy cheeks, cold hands, and elevated body temperature could be consistent with erythromelalgia, a rare condition characterized by episodes of redness, warmth, and burning pain in the extremities. The inability to stand up and frequent falls may be due to the discomfort caused by this condition.

	 2, Kawasaki Disease, 15,  The patient displays symptoms such as rash on cheeks, red cuticles, and flu-like ache which are suggestive of Kawasaki Disease, an autoimmune condition that primarily affects children. 
	 3, Lyme Disease, 10,  The presence of cuts on hands, tiredness, bumps under arms, and trouble swallowing solids could be indicative of Lyme Disease, a tick-borne illness that can present with a variety of symptoms including joint pain and rash.
	 4, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 3,  Symptoms such as rash on eyelids, tiredness, difficulty swallowing, and joint pain are consistent with Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), an autoimmune disease that can affect multiple organs including the skin and joints.
	 5, Food Allergy, 2,  The symptoms of rash on hands, rash on cheeks, and trouble swallowing solids may suggest a food allergy as a possible cause, especially if there is a history of exposure to allergens.

	 Malar Rash
	 Gottron Papule
	 Periungal Erythema
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Shawl Sign
	 Edema
	 Fatigue
	 Falling Episodes
	 Lymphadenopathy
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Dyspnea on Exertion
Translated Symptoms:
	 Rosy cheeks
	 Hand rash
	 Red Cuticles
	 Cannot raise arms
	 Rash on Chest and Back
	 Hand swelling
	 Tiredness
	 Loss of Coordination
	 Bumps under arms
	 Dark eyelids
	 Trouble breathing with activity
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 70,  The patient presents with a classic triad of muscle weakness (difficulty raising arms), skin rash (rosy cheeks, hand rash, rash on chest and back), and systemic symptoms (tiredness). 
	 2, Kawasaki Disease, 20,  The patient has hand swelling, red cuticles, bumps under arms, and dark eyelids which are consistent with Kawasaki disease. 
	 3, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 5,  The combination of rosy cheeks, tiredness, loss of coordination, and rash on chest and back can be seen in SLE. 
	 4, Allergic Reaction, 3,  The hand swelling, rash on chest and back, and trouble breathing with activity could be indicative of an allergic reaction. 
	 5, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 2,  The patient's symptoms of hand swelling, joint pain (cannot raise arms), and rash on the chest and back are suggestive of juvenile idiopathic arthritis.

	 2, Lupus, 20,  The symptoms of rash on knuckles, rosy cheeks, bumps on neck, fatigue, joint swelling, and purple eyelids are suggestive of Lupus, especially in a young female patient.
	 3, Dermatomyositis, 10,  The combination of rash on knuckles, difficulty walking up stairs, fatigue, and purple eyelids may indicate Dermatomyositis, a rare inflammatory disease affecting the skin and muscles.

	 5, Systemic Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 5,  The symptoms of joint swelling, stuck joint, fatigue, and rash on knuckles are also consistent with Systemic Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, a subtype of JIA with systemic features.

	 Rosy cheeks
	 Rash that comes on in sun
	 Hand rash
	 Tiredness
	 Fever
	 Loss of Coordination
	 Muscle Weakness
	 Rash on Chest and Back
	 Tender gums
Responses:
	 1, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus, 40,  The patient presents with a butterfly rash on the face (rosy cheeks), photosensitivity rash, fatigue, fever, and muscle weakness which are all consistent with systemic lupus erythematosus.
	 2, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 25,  Symptoms such as rash on the hands, muscle weakness, fatigue, and rash on the chest and back are suggestive of juvenile dermatomyositis, an autoimmune disorder that affects skin and muscles in children.
	 3, Kawasaki Disease, 15,  The combination of fever, rash on the hands, tender gums, and rosy cheeks may indicate Kawasaki disease, an inflammatory condition that affects blood vessels in children.
	 4, Lyme Disease, 10,  Loss of coordination along with rash, fatigue, and fever could be indicative of Lyme disease, which is a common tick-borne illness.
	 5, Vitamin D Deficiency, 5,  Muscle weakness along with fatigue could be due to vitamin D deficiency, especially in a child who may not be getting enough sunlight exposure for adequate vitamin D synthesis.

	 Malar Rash
Translated Symptoms:

	 Big lymph nodes
	 Rash on hands
	 Weight Loss
	 Red Cuticles
	 Trouble swallowing solids
	 Rash on cheeks
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 40,  The patient presents with purple eyelids, big lymph nodes, rash on hands, weight loss, and red cuticles, which are consistent with systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis. The rash on cheeks and trouble swallowing solids can also be seen in some cases of this condition.
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 25,  The combination of purple eyelids, rash on hands, weight loss, red cuticles, and rash on cheeks could be indicative of systemic lupus erythematosus, especially in a pediatric patient. The presence of big lymph nodes is less common but can still be seen in some cases of SLE.
	 3, Kawasaki Disease, 15,  Kawasaki disease can present with symptoms such as rash on hands, red cuticles, and rash on cheeks in pediatric patients. The presence of big lymph nodes and trouble swallowing solids can also be seen in Kawasaki disease. 
	 4, Lymphoma, 10,  The combination of big lymph nodes, weight loss, and trouble swallowing solids could raise suspicion for a lymphoma in this patient. The presence of other symptoms such as purple eyelids and rash on hands would be less typical but can still be seen in some cases.
	 5, Langerhans Cell Histiocytosis, 5,  Langerhans cell histiocytosis can present with symptoms such as rash on hands, big lymph nodes, weight loss, and rash on cheeks. The presence of purple eyelids and trouble swallowing solids would be less common but can still be seen in some cases of this condition.

Trial # 524
Original Symptoms:
	 Raynaud's Syndrome
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Edema
	 Muscle Pain and Tenderness
	 Malar Rash
	 Lymphadenopathy
	 Periungal Erythema
	 Fatigue
Translated Symptoms:
	 Fingers turning white
	 Exercise intolerance
	 Leg swelling
	 Leg pain
	 Rash on face
	 Bumps under arms
	 Red Cuticles
	 Fatigue
Responses:
	 1, Raynaud's Phenomenon, 60,  The patient's symptoms of fingers turning white, exercise intolerance, and leg swelling are consistent with Raynaud's phenomenon, a condition characterized by vasospasm of small arteries in response to cold or stress. 
	 2, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 20,  The patient's symptoms of leg pain, rash on face, bumps under arms, and red cuticles may be indicative of juvenile idiopathic arthritis, an autoimmune condition that can present with joint pain, skin rashes, and nail abnormalities.
	 3, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 10,  The patient's symptoms of rash on face, bumps under arms, red cuticles, and fatigue could be suggestive of systemic lupus erythematosus, a chronic autoimmune disease that can affect various organs including the skin and joints.
	 4, Hypothyroidism, 5,  The patient's symptoms of fatigue, exercise intolerance, and leg swelling could be related to hypothyroidism, a condition where the thyroid gland does not produce enough hormones.
	 5, Chronic Fatigue Syndrome, 5,  The patient's symptoms of fatigue, exercise intolerance, and leg pain could be consistent with chronic fatigue syndrome, a complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that cannot be explained by any underlying medical condition.

	 Dark eyelids
	 Cannot stand up
	 Rash on hands
Responses:

Additionally, the inability to stand up may be indicative of muscle weakness or joint pain commonly seen in lupus.
	 2, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 20,  The combination of rash on the hands, frequent falls, and difficulty standing up could be suggestive of juvenile dermatomyositis, an autoimmune condition that affects the skin and muscles in children.

	 5, Contact Dermatitis, 5,  The rash on the chest, back, and hands may be indicative of contact dermatitis, especially if the rash worsens in the sun. It could explain the red cuticles as well.

	 2, Systemic lupus erythematosus, 30,  The combination of rash on knuckles, dark eyelids, red cuticles, fever, and fingers turning white could be indicative of systemic lupus erythematosus, especially in a young female patient. 
	 3, Dermatomyositis, 15,  The presence of rash on knuckles, dark eyelids, coordination issues, and difficulty washing hair may suggest dermatomyositis, a rare inflammatory disease that affects the skin and muscles. 
	 4, Raynaud's phenomenon, 10,  The symptoms of fingers turning white and possibly coordination issues could be related to Raynaud's phenomenon, a condition that affects blood flow to the extremities. 
	 5, Kawasaki disease, 5,  The combination of fever, rash on knuckles, and red cuticles may raise suspicion for Kawasaki disease, an illness that primarily affects children and causes inflammation in the blood vessels.

	 3, Kawasaki Disease, 15,  Kawasaki disease can present with fever, rash, hand rash, and finger turning blue due to potential vasculitis. The patient's fatigue and muscle pain can also be seen in this condition.
	 4, Systemic Scleroderma, 10,  Systemic scleroderma can present with hand rash, finger turning blue (due to Raynaud's phenomenon), fatigue, and muscle pain. The shortness of breath may be related to pulmonary involvement seen in this condition.
	 5, Dermatomyositis, 5,  Dermatomyositis can present with muscle pain, fatigue, hand rash, and potentially finger turning blue. The patient's shortness of breath may be related to interstitial lung disease associated with dermatomyositis.

	 Fatigue
	 Fever
	 Can't tolerate sunlight exposure
	 Flu like ache
	 Sores on hands
	 Red Cuticles
	 Cannot sit up
	 Shortness of breath
Responses:
	 1, Raynaud's phenomenon, 50,  The patient's symptoms of finger turning blue, joint swelling, and fatigue are consistent with Raynaud's phenomenon, a condition where blood vessels in the extremities constrict in response to cold or stress.
	 2, Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), 30,  The combination of symptoms like joint swelling, fatigue, fever, photosensitivity, flu-like ache, and sores on hands can be seen in SLE, an autoimmune disease that can affect various organs in the body.
	 3, Juvenile idiopathic arthritis, 10,  The symptoms of joint swelling, fatigue, and fever could be indicative of juvenile idiopathic arthritis, a condition that causes joint inflammation in children.
	 4, Systemic sclerosis, 5,  The presence of finger turning blue, joint swelling, red cuticles, and shortness of breath may suggest systemic sclerosis, a connective tissue disease that can affect the skin, blood vessels, and internal organs.
	 5, Systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis, 5,  The symptoms of joint swelling, fever, fatigue, and inability to sit up could be consistent with systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis, a subtype of juvenile idiopathic arthritis characterized by systemic inflammation.

	 Gottron Papule

Translated Symptoms:
	 Joint swelling
	 Activity intolerance
	 Rosy cheeks
	 Trouble breathing with activity
	 Arm swelling
	 Fingers turning white
	 Fatigue
	 Rash on knuckles
	 Rash on eyelids
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 60,  Joint swelling, activity intolerance, rosy cheeks, arm swelling, and fatigue are all consistent with Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, which can present with systemic symptoms such as fatigue and rosy cheeks, along with joint involvement.
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 30,  Joint swelling, rosy cheeks, trouble breathing with activity, rash on knuckles, and rash on eyelids are suggestive of SLE, which is an autoimmune condition that can affect multiple organ systems including the skin and joints.
	 3, Raynaud's Phenomenon, 5,  Fingers turning white, joint swelling, and arm swelling can be seen in Raynaud's Phenomenon, a condition characterized by vasospasm of the blood vessels in response to cold or stress.
	 4, Kawasaki Disease, 3,  Rash on eyelids, rosy cheeks, joint swelling, and arm swelling can be seen in Kawasaki Disease, a rare childhood illness that can cause inflammation in blood vessels throughout the body.
	 5, Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma), 2,  Joint swelling, fatigue, and trouble breathing with activity can be seen in Systemic Sclerosis, an autoimmune condition that can lead to skin thickening, joint pain, and internal organ involvement.

	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 20,  The patient's symptoms of rash that worsens in the sun, red cuticles, rosy cheeks, and hand rash are suggestive of systemic lupus erythematosus, especially in the presence of fatigue and weight loss.
	 3, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 10,  The joint symptoms (cannot raise arms), rash, and fatigue could be indicative of juvenile idiopathic arthritis, which can present with systemic features such as tiredness and rash.
	 4, Systemic Sclerosis, 5,  The presence of hand rash, red cuticles, trouble breathing (possible lung involvement), and weight loss may be seen in systemic sclerosis, a connective tissue disorder.

	 2, Rheumatic Fever, 20,  Fatigue, rosy cheeks, elevated body temperature, and red cuticles can be seen in rheumatic fever, a complication of untreated strep throat that can affect the heart, joints, skin, and brain.

	 5, Kawasaki Disease, 5,  Fever, hand rash, and red cuticles are common in Kawasaki disease, an illness that primarily affects children and can cause inflammation in blood vessels, leading to symptoms like rash, fever, and swollen lymph nodes.

	 Muscle Pain and Tenderness
	 Gingivitis
	 Fatigue
	 Periungal Erythema
	 Malar Rash
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Photosensitive Rashes
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Gottron Papule
	 Arthritis
Translated Symptoms:
	 Flu like ache
	 Painful gums
	 Tiredness
	 Red Cuticles
	 Rash on cheeks
	 Rash on eyelids
	 Can't tolerate sunlight exposure
	 Exercise intolerance
	 Rash on knuckles
	 Hard to move joints
Responses:
	 1, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus, 60,  The patient presents with a combination of symptoms including rash on the cheeks and eyelids, rash on knuckles, painful gums, red cuticles, intolerance to sunlight exposure, fatigue, and joint pain, which are consistent with systemic lupus erythematosus.
	 2, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 20,  The patient's symptoms of joint pain, rash on knuckles, and exercise intolerance may suggest juvenile idiopathic arthritis as a possible diagnosis.
	 3, Porphyria, 10,  Symptoms such as rash on the cheeks, eyelids, and knuckles, along with intolerance to sunlight exposure, tiredness, and flu-like aches, could be indicative of porphyria, a group of disorders that affect the skin or nervous system.
	 4, Rheumatic Fever, 5,  The patient's presentation of joint pain, rash on the cheeks, fatigue, and flu-like aches may raise suspicion for rheumatic fever, especially in a pediatric patient.
	 5, Systemic Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 5,  Considering the patient's symptoms of joint pain, rash on knuckles, and systemic features such as fatigue and exercise intolerance, systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis is also a possible diagnosis to consider.

	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 25,  The symptoms of fatigue, rash on face, rash on hands, red cuticles, and dark eyelids are suggestive of systemic lupus erythematosus. Additionally, flu-like aches can also be seen in patients with SLE.

	 Periungal Erythema

	 Weight Loss
Translated Symptoms:
	 Cannot sit up
	 Fingers turning white
	 Contracture
	 Trouble breathing
	 Fatigue
	 Red gums
	 Red Cuticles
	 Rash on Back
	 Rash on hands
	 Loss of Weight
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 60,  The patient's symptoms of contracture, trouble breathing, fatigue, rash on hands, and weight loss are consistent with juvenile idiopathic arthritis, which can present with joint stiffness, systemic symptoms, and skin manifestations.
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 20,  The combination of fatigue, rash on back, rash on hands, weight loss, and red gums may indicate a possibility of systemic lupus erythematosus, an autoimmune condition that can affect multiple organs including the skin and joints.
	 3, Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma), 10,  The presence of fingers turning white, contracture, trouble breathing, and red cuticles could suggest systemic sclerosis, a connective tissue disorder that can cause skin thickening, vascular symptoms, and internal organ involvement.
	 4, Kawasaki Disease, 5,  The symptoms of red gums, rash on back, rash on hands, and weight loss may be seen in Kawasaki disease, an inflammatory condition that affects blood vessels and can lead to systemic symptoms.
	 5, Cystic Fibrosis, 5,  While less likely given the age and symptoms, the combination of trouble breathing, weight loss, and fatigue could potentially be seen in cystic fibrosis, a genetic disorder that affects the lungs and digestive system.

	 2, Raynaud's phenomenon, 20,  The symptom of finger turning blue is indicative of Raynaud's phenomenon, a condition where blood vessels in the fingers and toes spasm in response to cold or stress, causing them to turn blue or white.

	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 60,  The patient has a rash on the cheeks (malar rash), photosensitivity (can't tolerate sunlight exposure), fatigue, and weight loss which are common symptoms of SLE, an autoimmune disease that can affect multiple organs including the skin and joints.

Weight loss may also occur due to decreased appetite and energy expenditure associated with the condition.
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 30,  The combination of rash on cheeks (butterfly rash), tiredness, red cuticles, and enlarged lymph nodes raises suspicion for systemic lupus erythematosus, especially in a young female. Joint pain and muscle weakness may also manifest as leg pain and difficulty raising arms.
	 3, Leukemia, 15,  Weight loss, tiredness, rash on cheeks, enlarged lymph nodes, and leg pain can be seen in leukemia. The presence of red cuticles may indicate underlying hematologic abnormalities. 
	 4, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 10,  Symptoms of tiredness, rash on cheeks, red cuticles, leg pain, and difficulty raising arms are consistent with juvenile dermatomyositis, an autoimmune condition affecting the skin and muscles in children. Enlarged lymph nodes may also be present due to the inflammatory nature of the disease.
	 5, Kawasaki disease, 5,  Kawasaki disease can present with rash on cheeks, red cuticles, tiredness, leg pain, and enlarged lymph nodes. The combination of these symptoms in a young child raises suspicion for this condition. Weight loss may occur due to systemic inflammation and decreased appetite.

	 1, Kawasaki disease, 40,  Kawasaki disease is a rare childhood illness that causes inflammation in the walls of medium-sized arteries throughout the body. Symptoms include fever, rash on hands and face, red cuticles, and tiredness. It can also present with trouble swallowing and shortness of breath.
	 2, Streptococcal pharyngitis (Strep throat), 25,  Strep throat can present with fever, trouble swallowing, rash on hands and face, tiredness, and red cuticles. It can lead to complications such as scarlet fever which presents with a characteristic rash on the hands and face.
	 3, Asthma exacerbation, 15,  Shortness of breath, fever, and activity intolerance can be seen in an asthma exacerbation. The patient may also experience tiredness and may have a rash due to allergic reactions or medications.
	 4, Scarlet fever, 10,  Scarlet fever is a bacterial infection caused by group A Streptococcus bacteria. It can present with fever, rash on the hands and face, red cuticles, and tiredness. It can also lead to trouble swallowing due to a sore throat.
	 5, Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), 5,  SLE is an autoimmune disease that can present with fever, rash on face and hands, fatigue, and shortness of breath. Red cuticles and trouble swallowing may also occur due to inflammation in the body.

	 Edema
	 Arthritis
	 Malar Rash
	 Weight Loss
	 Falling Episodes
	 Fatigue
	 Lymphadenopathy
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Fever
	 Raynaud's Syndrome
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Interstitial Lung Disease
	 Muscle Pain and Tenderness
	 Joint Contracture
Translated Symptoms:
	 Arm swelling
	 Joint pain
	 Rash on cheeks
	 Weight Loss
	 Coordination Issues
	 Tiredness
	 Bumps under arms
	 Rash on eyelids
	 Elevated Body Temperature
	 Cold hands
	 Cannot raise arms
	 Shorness of breath
	 Arm pain
	 Joint stuck
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 60,  The patient presents with joint pain, arm swelling, rash on cheeks, bumps under arms, and joint stiffness which are all consistent with Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis.
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 20,  The patient has a rash on the cheeks (malar rash), rash on eyelids, joint pain, fatigue, and elevated body temperature, which are all suggestive of Systemic Lupus Erythematosus.
	 3, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 10,  The symptoms of arm swelling, joint pain, rash on eyelids, weight loss, coordination issues, and difficulty raising arms are indicative of Juvenile Dermatomyositis.
	 4, Hypothyroidism, 5,  The patient has weight loss, tiredness, cold hands, and joint pain which can be seen in hypothyroidism.
	 5, Juvenile Rheumatoid Arthritis, 5,  The symptoms of joint pain, arm swelling, coordination issues, and tiredness are characteristic of Juvenile Rheumatoid Arthritis.

	 4, Mononucleosis, 40,  The combination of fever, tiredness, flu-like ache, and weight loss may be seen in mononucleosis, which is common in children and can cause prolonged fatigue.

Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 50,  The patient presents with muscle weakness, rash on eyelids, rash that comes on in the sun, joint pain, and fatigue, which are all characteristic symptoms of juvenile dermatomyositis. Additionally, the presence of red cuticles and cuts on hands may suggest vasculitis commonly seen in this condition.
	 2, Lupus, 30,  The patient exhibits symptoms such as rash on knuckles, joint pain, fatigue, and rash on eyelids, which can be seen in lupus. The rash that comes on in the sun is also a common feature of lupus.
	 3, Systemic Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 15,  Symptoms like joint pain, muscle weakness, fatigue, and rash on knuckles can be indicative of systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis. The presence of painful gums may suggest underlying systemic inflammation seen in this condition.
	 4, Cutaneous Mastocytosis, 5,  The bumps on the neck and rash that comes on in the sun could be consistent with cutaneous mastocytosis, a condition characterized by skin lesions that worsen with sun exposure. Additionally, the patient's red cuticles and cuts on hands may be related to mast cell activation seen in this disorder.
	 5, Vitamin D deficiency, 5,  Muscle weakness, joint pain, fatigue, and rash on eyelids can be associated with vitamin D deficiency. The patient's age and possibly inadequate sun exposure may contribute to this deficiency, leading to the symptoms described.
Trial # 1745
Original Symptoms:
	 Falling Episodes
	 Fatigue
	 Photosensitive Rashes
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Periungal Erythema
	 Dysphagia
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Malar Rash
Translated Symptoms:
	 Coordination Issues
	 Tiredness
	 Can't tolerate sunlight exposure
	 Purple eyelids
	 Red Cuticles
	 Trouble swallowing solids
	 Cannot walk up stairs
	 Rash on cheeks
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile dermatomyositis, 60,  The patient's symptoms of coordination issues, tiredness, intolerance to sunlight, purple eyelids, red cuticles, trouble swallowing solids, difficulty walking up stairs, and rash on cheeks are consistent with the presentation of juvenile dermatomyositis, which is a rare autoimmune disease that causes muscle weakness and skin rash.
	 2, Lupus, 20,  Lupus is another autoimmune disease that can present with a rash on the cheeks (also known as a "butterfly rash"), tiredness, coordination issues, photosensitivity (intolerance to sunlight), and muscle weakness. It is less likely than juvenile dermatomyositis due to the absence of some key symptoms like trouble swallowing solids.
	 3, Polymyositis, 10,  Polymyositis is an autoimmune disease that causes muscle weakness and can present with symptoms such as coordination issues, tiredness, trouble swallowing solids, and difficulty walking up stairs. The absence of some symptoms like the rash on the cheeks makes it less likely than juvenile dermatomyositis.
	 4, Sjogren's syndrome, 5,  Sjogren's syndrome is an autoimmune condition that can cause dryness of the eyes and mouth, fatigue, and muscle weakness. While it can present with some overlapping symptoms like tiredness and difficulty swallowing solids, it is less likely in this case due to the absence of other key symptoms like the rash on the cheeks.
	 5, Systemic sclerosis (scleroderma), 5,  Systemic sclerosis is a connective tissue disease that can cause skin thickening, fatigue, muscle weakness, and difficulty swallowing solids. While some symptoms overlap with the patient's presentation, the absence of other key symptoms like the rash on the cheeks makes it less likely than juvenile dermatomyositis.

	 3, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 10,  The combination of hand rash, tiredness, rash on eyelids, and fever could be indicative of systemic lupus erythematosus, an autoimmune disease that can affect various organs including the skin and joints.
	 4, Rheumatic Fever, 5,  The presence of fever, joint pain, and rash on the eyelids raises suspicion for rheumatic fever, a rare inflammatory condition that can follow a streptococcal infection.
	 5, Kawasaki Disease, 5,  The symptoms of fever, rash on eyelids, and hand rash may suggest Kawasaki disease, an inflammatory condition that primarily affects children and can lead to blood vessel inflammation.

	 4, Allergic Reaction, 10,  The rash on the face and eyelids, along with bumps on the neck, could be indicative of an allergic reaction. Shortness of breath and fatigue can also be seen in severe allergic reactions.
	 5, Chronic Kidney Disease, 5,  Leg swelling, weight loss, and shortness of breath can be signs of Chronic Kidney Disease. Additionally, fatigue and red cuticles can be associated with kidney dysfunction.

	 Rash on hands

Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 60,  This autoimmune condition presents with characteristic skin rashes on the face, eyelids, and hands, along with muscle weakness (difficulty walking up stairs) and fatigue. Trouble swallowing can also occur due to muscle weakness.
	 2, Lupus, 20,  Lupus can cause a facial rash, sun-sensitive rash, joint pain (flu-like aches), and fatigue. The presence of red cuticles may also be associated with this condition.
	 3, Lyme Disease, 10,  Lyme disease can present with flu-like symptoms, joint pain, and fatigue. The rash that comes on in the sun may be indicative of a photosensitive rash seen in Lyme disease.
	 4, Kawasaki Disease, 5,  Kawasaki disease can cause a rash on the face and hands, along with redness around the cuticles. It can also lead to fatigue and difficulty walking due to joint pain.
	 5, Scarlet Fever, 5,  Scarlet fever can present with a rash on the face, hands, and eyelids, along with flu-like symptoms and tiredness. The red cuticles may be a sign of the typical "strawberry tongue" seen in Scarlet Fever.

Translated Symptoms:

	 2, Juvenile idiopathic arthritis, 20,  The combination of hand rash, leg pain, arm swelling, and fatigue could be indicative of juvenile idiopathic arthritis, a common autoimmune condition in children that can present with joint pain, swelling, and rash.
	 3, Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), 10,  Purple eyelids, hand rash, fatigue, and joint symptoms may be seen in pediatric SLE, a multisystem autoimmune disease that can affect various organs including the skin and joints.

	 5, Kawasaki disease, 5,  The combination of hand rash, leg pain, arm swelling, and inability to sit up could be consistent with Kawasaki disease, an inflammatory condition that predominantly affects young children and can lead to systemic vasculitis.

Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 60,  Juvenile Dermatomyositis is a rare autoimmune disease that causes muscle weakness, joint swelling, rash on cheeks, tiredness, and trouble swallowing. It commonly affects children between the ages of 5 to 15 years old.
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 20,  SLE can present with joint swelling, rash on cheeks (malar rash), rash on hands, rash on back, and sunlight sensitivity. It is more common in females and can affect children as well.
	 3, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, 10,  Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis can cause joint swelling, rash on cheeks, tiredness, and arm swelling. It is a common autoimmune condition in children.
	 4, Polymyositis, 5,  Polymyositis is an inflammatory muscle disease that can present with muscle weakness, tiredness, trouble swallowing, and joint swelling.
	 5, Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma), 5,  Systemic Sclerosis can lead to joint swelling, trouble swallowing, arm swelling, and intolerance to sunlight. It is a rare autoimmune condition that can affect children.

	 3, Muscular Dystrophy, 15,  The patient's symptoms of difficulty walking up stairs, frequent falls, and fatigue could be indicative of Muscular Dystrophy, a genetic disorder that causes progressive weakness and muscle loss.

	 Coordination Issues
	 Loss of Weight
	 Red Cuticles
	 Fatigue
	 Butterfly rash
	 Cannot wash hair
	 Bumps on neck
	 Purple eyelids
	 Hand rash
Responses:
	 1, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 70,  The patient presents with a butterfly rash, red cuticles, fatigue, bumps on the neck, and purple eyelids, all of which are consistent with the symptoms of SLE.
	 2, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis (JIA), 20,  Coordination issues along with hand rash could be indicative of JIA, a condition that affects joints and can cause coordination difficulties.
	 3, Dermatomyositis, 10,  The combination of purple eyelids, hand rash, and difficulty washing hair may suggest dermatomyositis, an inflammatory muscle disease with characteristic skin findings.
	 4, Anemia, 5,  Fatigue along with loss of weight could be due to anemia, a condition where the body lacks enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to tissues.
	 5, Malnutrition, 5,  The presence of weight loss, fatigue, and hand rash could be due to malnutrition, where the body is not receiving the necessary nutrients for proper function.

The patient's symptoms of muscle tenderness, fatigue, and difficulty walking up stairs could be consistent with Vitamin D deficiency, especially if there is inadequate sun exposure or dietary intake.

	 2, Lupus, 25,  Lupus can present with symptoms such as rash that worsens in the sun, fatigue, joint pain, and skin rashes on the face and eyelids, which are all seen in this patient.

	 Dyspnea on Exertion
	 Periungal Erythema
	 Heliotrope Rash
	 Fatigue
	 Weight Loss
	 Dysphagia
	 Progressive proximal muscles weakness
	 Gottron Papule
	 Raynaud's Syndrome
	 Malar Rash
Translated Symptoms:
	 Trouble breathing
	 Red Cuticles
	 Rash on eyelids
	 Fatigue
	 Loss of Weight
	 Trouble swallowing liquids
	 Muscle Weakness
	 Hand rash
	 Finger turning blue
	 Butterfly rash
Responses:
	 1, Juvenile Dermatomyositis, 50,  The patient presents with muscle weakness, fatigue, trouble swallowing, hand rash, and butterfly rash which are consistent with Juvenile Dermatomyositis.  
	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 30,  The patient has symptoms like butterfly rash, fatigue, hand rash, and trouble swallowing liquids which are commonly seen in SLE. 
	 3, Asthma, 10,  The patient is experiencing trouble breathing which could be indicative of asthma, especially if there is a history of allergies or family history of asthma. 
	 4, Raynaud's Phenomenon, 5,  The symptoms of finger turning blue and red cuticles are suggestive of Raynaud's phenomenon. 
	 5, Anorexia Nervosa, 5,  The patient's weight loss, fatigue, and trouble swallowing liquids could be indicative of anorexia nervosa.

	 3, Bacterial Infection, 10,  The combination of fever and red cuticles could be indicative of a bacterial infection, which may also cause muscle weakness leading to difficulty in raising arms.
	 4, Rheumatic Fever, 5,  Rheumatic fever can present with fever, joint pain, and muscle weakness which could result in difficulty raising arms.

	 2, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 30,  Systemic Lupus Erythematosus is an autoimmune disease that can present with photosensitivity (can't tolerate sunlight exposure), rash (including a hand rash), fatigue, joint pain (can't move joint), and muscle weakness. 	 3, Xeroderma Pigmentosum, 10,  Xeroderma Pigmentosum is a rare genetic disorder that causes extreme sensitivity to sunlight, leading to severe sunburns and an increased risk of skin cancer. The bumps under the arms may be related to skin changes associated with this condition.
	 4, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis (JIA), 5,  Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis is a common autoimmune condition in children that can present with joint pain, fatigue, and difficulty with movement. The hand rash and inability to sit up may be related to joint inflammation and pain.
	 5, Dermatitis Herpetiformis, 5,  Dermatitis Herpetiformis is a skin manifestation of celiac disease characterized by itchy bumps and blisters, typically found on the elbows, knees, and buttocks. The hand rash and bumps under the arms may be consistent with this condition.

	 2, Kawasaki Disease, 20,  There is a presence of fever, rash on the face and hands, arm swelling, red cuticles, and big lymph nodes, which are all consistent with Kawasaki Disease. Additionally, the patient has an elevated body temperature.
	 3, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), 15,  The patient has a rash on the face and eyelids, along with fatigue, weight loss, and big lymph nodes. SLE can present with a variety of systemic symptoms and skin manifestations.
	 4, Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia, 10,  The symptoms of weight loss, tiredness, big lymph nodes, and rash on face can be seen in Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia. Additionally, the patient has exercise intolerance which may be related to the disease.
	 5, Stevens-Johnson Syndrome, 5,  The presence of skin rashes on the face, hands, eyelids, and red cuticles can be seen in Stevens-Johnson Syndrome. This condition can also present with fever and systemic symptoms.
